# Employee Directory — Coding Rules

Apply these rules to all work in this project. If a requirement is ambiguous, **ask before assuming**.

## Principles

- Prefer small, single-purpose functions and modules
- Name things for intent; avoid clever or opaque code
- Keep components thin; put data and lifecycle logic in hooks/utils
- Surface specific errors early; avoid generic catch-all messages when a typed error exists
- Prefer lookup maps and early returns over branching trees

## Guarded clauses (prefer over if/else)

Use early returns and guard clauses. Avoid `if/else` chains when a guard, map, or ternary-free early exit works.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
function label(status: Status) {
  if (status === "started") {
    return "Starting…";
  } else if (status === "inProgress") {
    return "Working…";
  } else {
    return "Done";
  }
}

// ✅ GOOD
function label(status: Status) {
  const labels: Record<Status, string> = {
    started: "Starting…",
    inProgress: "Working…",
    finished: "Done",
    idle: "",
  };
  return labels[status];
}
```

```ts
// ❌ BAD
function save(employee: Employee | null) {
  if (employee) {
    return api.update(employee);
  } else {
    throw new Error("Missing employee");
  }
}

// ✅ GOOD
function save(employee: Employee | null) {
  if (!employee) {
    throw new ValidationError("Employee is required before saving");
  }
  return api.update(employee);
}
```

## No nested for-loops

Do not nest `for` / `for…of` / `forEach` loops. Use `.filter`, `.map`, `.sort`, or a `Map`/`Set` for lookups.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
for (const employee of employees) {
  for (const term of terms) {
    // …
  }
}

// ✅ GOOD
const termSet = new Set(terms.map((t) => t.toLowerCase()));
const matches = employees.filter((employee) =>
  termSet.has(employee.department.toLowerCase())
);
```

## Clarification

When requirements, UX copy, data shape, or error behavior is unclear — **stop and ask** before choosing an approach.
